00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:29.540
or sports stars, like, kind of all the media
around Tiger Woods and--

00:18:29.540 --> 00:18:30.540
&gt;&gt;Zach: Sure.

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:31.540
&gt;&gt;membermale1: his slew of--

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:33.340
&gt;&gt;Zach: His incredible conquest--

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:34.340
&gt;&gt;membermale1: Yes.

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:35.340
&gt;&gt;Zach: record, yes.

00:18:35.340 --> 00:18:36.340
&gt;&gt;membermale1: Exactly. And, and, another--

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:39.500
&gt;&gt;Zach: I mean, he is a cute guy, but you
know, he's got kind of a built-in advantage

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:43.920
of having so much cash. You know, yesterday
I was sitting in a, in a restaurant here in

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:47.560
San Francisco, eating lunch and they had the
TV on with the sound off and it was one of

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:52.740
these, sort of, sports, sports writer, round
table discussion shows featuring, you know,

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:57.670
these crusty, ancient, dinosaur sports columnists
from newspapers around the country. And they

00:18:57.670 --> 00:19:00.750
had a, you know, it was one of these things
that you see on CNN or ESPN, where there's

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:05.500
the four screen, the four sections of the
screen and it's one man's face in each of

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:08.500
the screens and they were all talking. And
I don't even know what they were talking about

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:12.520
because the sound was off. And these four,
old, white dudes were sitting up there like

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:16.170
and they're all talking, they were moving
their hands and like, gesticulating at one

00:19:16.170 --> 00:19:20.810
another and you couldn't hear 'em and you
lost nothing with the sound being off. I mean,

00:19:20.810 --> 00:19:26.020
it's like, a lot of the-, it's, this is not
unique to sports, obviously. This is a sort

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:30.660
of a plague that infests our culture, but
a lot of the discussion about sports in this

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:36.330
country is just people talking, and not saying
anything. The appetite for sports information

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:41.390
and the sort of commercial demand for it has
grown to the point where 90% of what you see

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:45.960
and hear and read it, about sports isn't really
about sports at all. It's about the business

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:50.970
side of things, or celebrity gossip about,
you know, whatever terrible offense against

00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:56.620
common decency that Ben Roethlisberger has
recently committed. And, I, I guess part of

00:19:56.620 --> 00:20:01.930
the reason I wrote the book was the desire
to cut through all of that, not saying that

00:20:01.930 --> 00:20:05.840
mainstream sports or big time sports are illegitimate,
obviously they have a huge audience, and I'm

00:20:05.840 --> 00:20:12.450
part of that audience. But, to say that, you
know, that stuff is not what really what sport

00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:17.760
is about. I mean, sport is about experiencing
things, doing things that you otherwise wouldn't

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:23.630
do, having fun, and getting out there and
being part of the world rather than passively

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:29.030
sitting back and listening to this endless
stream of garbage about Tiger Woods or what

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:33.710
are, you know, whatever the topic du jour
is. So, I guess that's, you know, my response

00:20:33.710 --> 00:20:38.680
that I would give. The book is sort of an
attempt to kind of like, claw some real meaning

00:20:38.680 --> 00:20:42.650
out of sports and drag it away from those
people that are just, you know, jabber jawing

00:20:42.650 --> 00:20:43.650
about it all the time.

00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:45.740
Miss.

